Wash and dry produce.

Core, deseed, and dice @bell pepper{1}(core, deseeded, and diced into ½-inch pieces).

Peel @sweet potato{1}(peeled and diced into ½-inch pieces) if desired.

Peel and grate or mince @garlic{1%clove}(peeled and grated or minced) and @ginger{1%thumb}(peeled and grated or minced).

Halve, peel, and finely dice @yellow onion{1}(peeled and finely diced).

Zest and quarter lime.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @cornstarch{1%tablespoon} and 1 TBSP water (2 TBSP for 4). Set aside.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%teaspoon} in a large #pot{} over medium-high heat. Add bell pepper and sweet potato; season with @salt{1/4%tsp} (½ tsp for 4 servings) and @pepper{}.

Cook, stirring occasionally, until lightly browned, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Transfer to a #plate{}.

Heat another drizzle of oil in same pot over medium-high heat. Add garlic, ginger, and onion. Cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add @ground turkey{10%ounce} to pot with aromatics. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}. Season with @curry powder{1%tablespoon}, @salt{1/4%tsp} (½ tsp for 4 servings), and pepper.

Thoroughly shake @coconut milk{5.07%ounce} in container before opening.

Transfer veggies to pot with turkey mixture. Stir in @chicken stock concentrate{3}, cornstarch slurry, coconut milk, @sweet Thai chili sauce{1%ounce}, 1 1/2 cups water (3 cups for 4 servings), and @sugar{1%tablespoon} (2 TBSP for 4).

If cornstarch in slurry has settled, give it another stir now.

Bring to a boil, then reduce to a low simmer. Cook until flavors meld and sweet potato is tender, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> TIP: If soup seems too thick, add more water a splash at a time as needed.

Stir juice from two lime wedges (four wedges for 4 servings) into soup.

Season with salt and pepper to taste.

Divide between #bowls{}. Garnish with lime zest to taste. Serve with any remaining lime wedges on the side.